===Etymology===
{{borrowing|fr}} {{term|mayonnaise|lang=fr}}, named after the city {{w|Mahón}} whence the recipe was brought back to France.

The United States standard of identity comes from [http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/cfr_2002/aprqtr/21cfr169.140.htm 21&nbsp;CFR 169.140].

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈmeɪ.ə.neɪz/|/ˌmeɪ.əˈneɪz/|lang=en}}
* also {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/ˈmæn.eɪz/|[ˈmeən.eɪz]}}
* {{rhymes|eɪz}}
* The General American pronunciation {{IPA|/ˈmæn.eɪz/|[ˈmeən.eɪz]}} pronunciation is because of [[w:æ-tensing|æ-tensing]]. In many cases, the vowel has not actually flattened, but æ-tensing has caused many {{IPAchar|/æ/}} vowels (including in ''mayonnaise'') to tense to the phoneme {{IPAchar|[eə]}}. Sometimes this vowel is pronounced as a true {{IPAchar|[æ]}} anyway, because speakers interpret the ''-ayo-'' in ''mayonnaise'' as a {{IPAchar|/æ/}} phoneme due to conventional allophony. See also ''[[graham]]'', where æ-tensing has a similar effect.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# A [[dressing]] made from [[vegetable oil]], raw [[egg]] [[yolk]]s and [[seasoning]], used on [[salad]]s and in [[sandwich]]es.
## {{context|US|_|standard of identity}} An [[edible]] [[emulsified]] [[semisolid]] made of: [[vegetable oil]] (at least 65[[%]]); [[vinegar]] and/or [[lemon]] [[juice]]; raw egg ([[whole]] eggs or yolks); and, optionally, any of various [[flavor]]-related ingredients, [[sequestrant]]s, [[acid]]s{{,}} and [[crystallization]] [[inhibitor]]s.
#*: {{quote-journal|journal=Boys' Life| date=May| year=1985| page=20| books.google.com/books?id=tmYEAAAAMBAJ|
